// The `prelude.json` sub-module: the JSON boundary, over PLAIN Katari values. A JSON document is not a
// dedicated tree type — it is an ordinary value: a record / array / string / integer / number / boolean /
// null (the "document shape"). A program traverses a parsed reply with shape filters (`case record(r)` /
// `case array(a)` / `case string(s)`) and the total readers below, and builds one with ordinary record /
// array literals. Referenced by the default-import qualifier: `json.parse(...)`, `json.field(...)`.
//
// The naming law is the spine of this module: EVERY VERB IS LITERAL, save one. `parse`, `parse_as` and
// `stringify` move a document exactly as written — every object key is kept verbatim, and a `$`-prefixed
// key (`$ref`, `$constructor`) is an ordinary key, never a wire discriminator. The one exception is
// `to_text`, which renders a value's WIRE form as text (for display / a prompt / a handle embed): only it
// speaks the wire conventions (`$`-key escaping, `$constructor` / `$ref` tagging).
//
//   - `parse : string -> unknown`      text -> the document value (traverse it with shape filters)
//   - `parse_as[T] : string -> T`      literal parse + validation against T's schema (the typed text boundary)
//   - `stringify : unknown -> string`  a document value -> its document text (inverts `parse`)
//   - `to_text[T] : T -> string`       any value -> the JSON text of its wire form
//
// Laws: `stringify(parse(t)) == t` (document text, modulo number normalisation) and `parse(stringify(d)) == d`
// (a document value d).
//
// There is no `decode` and no `encode`. A document is ALREADY a value, so reading one needs no wire step:
// a plain value (record / array / scalar / file) drops straight into a document tree, and a document read
// from the outside becomes a value verbatim. The one place a wire form must be REVIVED — an AI replaying a
// `{ "$ref": ... }` handle into a tool argument that expects a `file` — is the delegation boundary's job:
// `reflection.call_agent` validates the argument against the callee's schema, and revives a `$ref` into a
// real `file` exactly where the schema expects one (schema-directed, never a blind lift).
//
// The `stringify` / `to_text` split is the sharpest edge of the literal / wire law:
//
//   - `stringify` is DOCUMENT-ONLY and its law is an IDENTITY: `stringify(parse(s)) == s` (modulo
//     whitespace / number normalisation), and `parse(stringify(d)) == d` for a document value d. A value
//     that is NOT a document — a `file`, a callable, or a `data` value — has no literal text form, so it
//     is rejected as a TYPED `stringify_error` (catchable), not silently coerced.
//   - `to_text` is TOTAL and its purpose is DISPLAY, not round-trip: it renders ANY value's wire form as
//     text (`$constructor` / `$ref` / `$$`-escaping and all). No identity law is promised — a document
//     with a literal `$ref` key comes back doubled — because the output is for a human / a prompt / a
//     handle embed, where seeing the wire form is the point.
//
// Errors: malformed text throws `parse_error`; a document that does not conform to the requested type's
// schema throws `decode_error` (from `parse_as`); a non-document value reaching `stringify` throws
// `stringify_error`.

@"A JSON document failed to parse: the text is not JSON. Thrown by `parse` / `parse_as`."
data parse_error(message: string)

@"A document does not conform to the requested type's schema. Thrown by `parse_as`; `message` names the
offending path."
data decode_error(message: string)

@"A value with no JSON document form — a `file`, a callable, or a `data` value — reached `stringify`.
Such a value has no literal text (only a wire form, which `to_text` renders); `message` names the
offending kind. Thrown by `stringify`."
data stringify_error(message: string)

@"Parse JSON text into its document value — a record / array / string / integer / number / boolean / null,
keys kept exactly as written (`$` is not interpreted). Traverse it with shape filters (`case record(r)`)
and the readers below, or pin its shape with `parse_as[T]`. A number without a fractional part parses as
`integer`. Malformed text throws `parse_error`."
primitive agent parse(@"The text of one complete JSON document." text: string) -> unknown with prelude.throw[parse_error]

@"Parse JSON text directly as a T, validated against T's schema — the typed text boundary, LITERAL like
`parse` (keys kept as written, `$` not interpreted). Instantiate T explicitly (it appears only in the
result, so it cannot be inferred). Malformed text throws `parse_error`; a schema mismatch throws
`decode_error` naming the offending path. A `$ref` an AI replayed is not revived here (this is literal) —
that happens at the delegation boundary, where the target's schema says a `file` is expected."
primitive agent parse_as[T](@"The text of one complete JSON document." text: string) -> T with prelude.throw[parse_error | decode_error]

@"Render a document value as its (compact) JSON text; the exact inverse of `parse` (keys verbatim, `$`
uninterpreted), so `stringify(parse(s))` is `s` up to whitespace. The value must be a document shape
(record / array / string / integer / number / boolean / null); a `file`, a callable or a `data` value has
no document text, so it throws `stringify_error`. To render an arbitrary value (wire form and all) as
text — where no round-trip is needed — use `to_text`."
primitive agent stringify(value: unknown) -> string with prelude.throw[stringify_error]

@"Render any value as the (compact) JSON text of its WIRE form, for DISPLAY (an error message, a handle
embed, a tool result rendered back to a model): a `data` value nests its fields under `value` (`{
$constructor: name, value: { ...fields } }`), a `file` becomes its `$ref` handle object, and an agent /
closure its `$agent` / `$closure` reference object. Total over every value. Keys read exactly as written —
a `$`-prefixed record key shows as itself, never doubled. No round-trip law is promised (unlike
`stringify`): because keys are shown verbatim, a record with a literal `$ref` key is indistinguishable in
the text from a `file` handle — an accepted ambiguity, since the point is to SEE the wire form, not to read
it back. A secret operand taints the whole result (the monotonic information-flow rule)."
primitive agent to_text[T](value: T) -> string

// The total readers — plain Katari over `unknown`, for picking values out of a document of unknown or
// irregular shape (an AI reply, a third-party API response) without a shape filter at every step. The
// subject parameter is named `target`, uniform with the other container lookups (`record.get`,
// `array.get`). Each reader is TOTAL: a missing key, an out-of-range index or a wrong shape yields `null` /
// `""` / an empty container rather than an error, so probes chain freely — `text(target = field(target =
// element(target = parsed, index = 0), key = "content"))` — and absence is checked once, at the end, where
// it matters. For a document whose shape IS known, prefer the typed boundary (`parse_as[T]`), which
// validates instead of defaulting. Where a genuine shape branch is wanted, use a shape filter
// directly (`match (node) { case record(r) -> ... case array(a) -> ... case _ -> node }`).

@"The record @target@ holds (its entries), or the empty record if @target@ is not a record."
agent entries(target: unknown) -> record[unknown] {
  match (target) {
    case record(record_value) -> record_value
    case _ -> record.empty()
  }
}

@"The array @target@ holds (its elements), or the empty array if @target@ is not an array."
agent items(target: unknown) -> array[unknown] {
  match (target) {
    case array(array_value) -> array_value
    case _ -> array.empty()
  }
}

@"The child at object key @key@ (`null` if @target@ is not a record or has no such key)."
agent field(target: unknown, key: string) -> unknown {
  match (target) {
    case record(record_value) -> record.get(target = record_value, key = key)
    case _ -> null
  }
}

@"The element at array index @index@ (`null` if @target@ is not an array or @index@ is out of range)."
agent element(target: unknown, index: integer) -> unknown {
  match (target) {
    case array(array_value) -> array.get(target = array_value, index = index)
    case _ -> null
  }
}

@"The string @target@ holds (the empty string if it is not a string)."
agent text(target: unknown) -> string {
  match (target) {
    case string(string_value) -> string_value
    case _ -> ""
  }
}
